  <section class="faq-section">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="faq-container">
        <h2 class="section-title">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
        <p class="section-subtitle">
          Common questions about our custom software development process in the
          UAE.
        </p>

        <div class="faq-list">
          <details>
            <summary>How long does it take to build custom software?</summary>
            <p>
              The timeline for building custom software varies based on the
              complexity of the project, the size of the development team, and
              the specific requirements. A simple application might take a few
              weeks, while a complex enterprise solution could take several
              months.
            </p>
          </details>
          <details>
            <summary
              >What is software architecture and why does it matter?</summary
            >
            <p>
              Software architecture defines the high-level structure of a system
              — how components are organized, how they communicate, how data
              flows, and how the system handles failure, load, and growth. Good
              architecture makes a system reliable, maintainable, and easy to
              extend. Poor architecture means that every new feature costs more
              than the last, the system becomes increasingly fragile, and
              eventually a rewrite becomes unavoidable.
            </p>
          </details>
          <details>
            <summary
              >When should we invest in a dedicated architecture phase?</summary
            >
            <p>
              Any time you are building a system that will need to scale, handle
              sensitive data, integrate with multiple external systems, or be
              maintained by a team over multiple years. It is also worth
              conducting an architectural review of existing systems before
              beginning a significant new phase of development, or if you are
              experiencing recurring performance problems, integration failures,
              or escalating maintenance costs.
            </p>
          </details>
          <details>
            <summary
              >What is the difference between microservices and a monolithic
              architecture?</summary
            >
            <p>
              A monolithic architecture bundles all application functionality
              into a single deployable unit. This is simpler to develop and
              operate initially but becomes difficult to scale and maintain as
              the system grows. A microservices architecture breaks the system
              into independently deployable services, each responsible for a
              specific capability. This enables independent scaling, faster
              deployment cycles, and clearer team ownership — but requires more
              sophisticated infrastructure and operational discipline. We help
              you evaluate which is appropriate for your stage and requirements.
            </p>
          </details>
          <details>
            <summary
              >Can you review and improve our existing architecture?</summary
            >
            <p>
              Yes. Our architecture review service assesses your existing system
              against best practices, identifies areas of technical debt and
              risk, and produces a prioritized remediation roadmap. This is
              often the right starting point before committing to a major new
              development phase.
            </p>
          </details>
          <details>
            <summary>What documentation do we receive?</summary>
            <p>
              Architecture engagements produce a comprehensive documentation
              package including component and sequence diagrams, data flow
              diagrams, API specifications, infrastructure blueprints, ADRs
              (Architecture Decision Records) explaining key decisions and their
              rationale, and an implementation guide for the development team.
            </p>
          </details>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

